It is appropriate that the day after Charlie Kirk’s memorial is #NationalFamilyDay. In his words,

“Having a family will change your life in the best ways, so get married and have kids. You won’t regret it."

Today, we honor the strength and unbreakable bond that defines family. There’s nothing more meaningful than being surrounded by those who stand by you, lift you up, and love you unconditionally. Take a moment to celebrate and cherish the people who matter most - today and every day.

Today, Americans across the country paused to honor the life and legacy of Charlie Kirk. His unwavering commitment to his faith, tireless advocacy for conservative causes, and fearless leadership inspired generations. Charlie will be deeply missed, but his impact will endure. Thank you for your service, Charlie. May you rest in peace.

This morning I had the opportunity to testify before the @NatResources  Subcommittee on Federal Lands regarding my bill, America’s National Churchill Museum National Historic Landmark Act. 

Nearly 80 years ago in 1946, Westminster College in Fulton, Missouri hosted one of the most consequential speeches of the 20th century. Winston Churchill's famous "Sinews of Peace" speech, which became known as the Iron Curtain speech.

With President Harry Truman at his side, Churchill warned the world of the division descending over Europe. Many historians mark that moment as the beginning of the Cold War.

I urge the committee to support this bill and ensure that America's National Churchill Museum receives the recognition it so clearly merits as a national historic landmark.
Thank you for having me this morning, it was my privilege!
